# 🔹 What is Searching?

Searching is the process of finding whether a given element (called the **key**) exists in a collection of data and, if it exists, determining its position.

Example:

Array:

```text
10 25 40 55 70
```

Search Key:

```text
40
```

Output:

```text
Found at index 2
```

Searching is one of the most fundamental operations in Computer Science and is heavily tested in GATE.

---

# 🔹 Types of Searching

There are two major searching techniques:

1. Linear Search
2. Binary Search

We will also study **Ternary Search**, which is useful in specific scenarios.

---

# 🔹 Linear Search

Linear Search checks every element one by one until the key is found.

---

## Algorithm

Given:

```text
15 22 8 31 10
```

Search key = 31

Comparison sequence:

```text
15 ❌
22 ❌
8 ❌
31 ✅
```

Element found after 4 comparisons.

---

## C Code

```c
for(i=0;i<n;i++)
{
    if(arr[i]==key)
        return i;
}
return -1;
```

---

## Complexity

### Best Case

Element found at first position.

[
O(1)
]

---

### Average Case

[
O(n)
]

---

### Worst Case

Element at last position or not present.

[
O(n)
]

---

### Advantages

* Simple implementation
* Works on both sorted and unsorted arrays

---

### Disadvantages

* Slow for large datasets

---

# 🔹 Binary Search

Binary Search repeatedly divides the search space into two halves.

📌 **Requirement: The array must be sorted.**

---

## Example

Sorted Array:

```text
5 10 20 30 40 50 60
```

Search Key = 40

Step 1:

Middle = 30

40 > 30

Search right half.

Step 2:

Middle = 50

40 < 50

Search left half.

Step 3:

Middle = 40

Found.

---

## Binary Search Algorithm

1. Calculate middle index.
2. Compare key with middle.
3. If equal → Found.
4. If smaller → Left half.
5. If larger → Right half.
6. Repeat.

---

## Recursive Recurrence

[
T(n)=T(n/2)+1
]

---

## Complexity

### Best Case

[
O(1)
]

---

### Average Case

[
O(\log n)
]

---

### Worst Case

[
O(\log n)
]

---

### Space Complexity

Iterative:

[
O(1)
]

Recursive:

[
O(\log n)
]

---

# 🔹 Binary Search Code

```c
while(low<=high)
{
    mid=(low+high)/2;

    if(arr[mid]==key)
        return mid;

    else if(key<arr[mid])
        high=mid-1;

    else
        low=mid+1;
}
```

---

# 🔹 Ternary Search

Ternary Search divides the array into **three equal parts**.

Two middle points:

[
mid_1
]

and

[
mid_2
]

Depending on the key, search continues in one of the three sections.

---

## Complexity

[
O(\log_3 n)
]

Although the logarithm base is 3, Ternary Search performs more comparisons per step.

In practice, **Binary Search is generally preferred**.

---

# 🔹 Comparison Table

| Feature               | Linear Search | Binary Search | Ternary Search |
| --------------------- | ------------- | ------------- | -------------- |
| Sorted Array Required | No            | Yes           | Yes            |
| Best Case             | O(1)          | O(1)          | O(1)           |
| Average Case          | O(n)          | O(log n)      | O(log₃ n)      |
| Worst Case            | O(n)          | O(log n)      | O(log₃ n)      |
| Space (Iterative)     | O(1)          | O(1)          | O(1)           |

